The Road to Nuclear Disarmament
NEW YORK – Mass destruction weapons and disarmament present one of the most challenging tasks that the world currently faces. One of my priorities as Secretary-General of the United Nations is to promote the global common good and find solutions to problems that transcend borders.
A world without nuclear weapons is a high-priority general good.
My interest in this topic partly stems from personal experiences.
My home country, South Korea, has suffered from the devastation of conventional warfare and was exposed to the threat of nuclear weapons and other mass destruction weapons.
Doch gibt es derartige Bedrohungsszenarien selbstverständlich nicht nur in Asien.
Obwohl der Einsatz von Atomwaffen seit langem als Tabu gilt, bleibt die Abrüstung lediglich eine Bestrebung.
Ist nun ein Tabu, das sich bloß auf den Einsatz solcher Waffen bezieht, überhaupt ausreichend?
Wenn es um Kernwaffen geht, treffen Einzelstaaten die wichtigsten Entscheidungen.
Doch spielt die UNO eine entscheidende Rolle dabei.
We offer a central forum where states can agree on norms that serve their shared interests.
We analyze and educate to achieve our agreed-upon goals and advocate for them.
Most states have decided to renounce nuclear weapons and have summarized their commitments under the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
However, some states view such weapons as status symbols, and others see them as the ultimate deterrent against an attack with nuclear weapons, which mainly explains the estimated 26,000 existing weapons.
Unfortunately, the doctrine of nuclear deterrence is contagious, making non-proliferation more difficult and creating new risks that nuclear weapons might be used.
