<s>Es gibt zudem Bedenken, dass uns eine „nukleare Renaissance“ bevorsteht, da Atomenergie in Zeiten zunehmender Anstrengungen zur Bekämpfung des Klimawandels als eine saubere Energiealternative angesehen wird.
<s>Die Hauptsorge besteht darin, dass dies zur Produktion und zum Einsatz von mehr Kernmaterial führen wird, das vor Verbreitung und terroristischen Bedrohungen geschützt werden muss.
<s>Die Hindernisse für die Abrüstung sind gewaltig.
<s>Doch erhalten die Kosten und Risiken ihrer Alternativen nie die Aufmerksamkeit, die sie verdienen.
Think about the enormous opportunity costs of high military budgets.
According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute (Stockholm International Peace Research Institute), military expenditures rose last year to over $1.3 trillion.
Ten years ago, the Brookings Institution published a study estimating the total cost of nuclear weapons alone in the United States to exceed $58 billion, including future decommissioning costs.
This is, by any definition, a massive investment that could have been directed towards many other productive goals.
Concerns about the costs of nuclear weapons and the dangers inherent in them have sparked a global idea fire, breathing new life into the cause of nuclear disarmament.
We have experienced the UN Commission on Disarmament under Hans Blix, the New Agenda Coalition, and Norway's Seven-Nation Initiative.
Australia and Japan have founded the International Commission for Nuclear Non-Proliferation and Disarmament.
Civil society groups and states with nuclear weapons have also put forward proposals, such as the Hoover Plan, introduced by Henry Kissinger.
I would like to propose my own Five-Point Plan.
Firstly: I call on all parties to the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, especially the nuclear powers, to live up to their treaty obligations and engage in negotiations for effective measures leading to nuclear disarmament.
They could agree on a framework agreement for separate, mutually reinforcing instruments.
Or they could negotiate an arms convention supported by a strong verification system, as has long been proposed in the UN.
I have circulated a draft for such a convention, which provides a good starting point, to all UN member states.
The nuclear powers should actively engage with this issue at the UN Disarmament Conference in Geneva, the only multilateral disarmament negotiation forum in the world, together with other states.
The world would also welcome a resumption of bilateral talks between the US and Russia aimed at significantly and verifiably reducing their arsenals.
The governments should also invest more in control research and development.
The UK's proposal for a conference of nuclear powers on the topic of control is a concrete step in the right direction.
Secondly: The permanent members of the Security Council should start discussing security issues in the process of nuclear disarmament.
They could clearly convey to states that do not possess nuclear weapons that they will not become victims of a nuclear weapons use or the threat thereof.
The Council could also convene a summit on nuclear disarmament.
States that are not parties to the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty should stop their nuclear weapon programs and enter into their own disarmament commitments.
Thirdly: Unilateral moratoriums on nuclear tests and the production of fissile materials may only be allowed to a limited extent.
We need new efforts to bring the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty into force, as well as incentives for the Disarmament Conference to immediately and without preconditions take up talks on a fissile material cutoff treaty.
I support the establishment of nuclear-weapon-free zones in Central Asia and Africa and strongly commend the efforts to establish such zones in the Middle East.
In addition, I urge all parties to the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty to conclude security arrangements with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and to voluntarily implement the stricter safeguards of the Additional Protocol.
